I have noticed a small discrepancy regarding how vertex shader are applied by `SpriteBatch`.

The following pass-through effect...

```
float4 PixelShaderFunction(float4 position : SV_Position, float4 color : COLOR0, float2 tex : TEXCOORD0) : COLOR0
{
    return tex2D(s0, tex) * color;
}

void SpriteVertexShader(inout float4 vColor : COLOR0, inout float2 texCoord : TEXCOORD0, inout float4 position : POSITION0) {
    position = mul(position, MatrixTransform);
}

technique Test
{
    pass Pass1
    {
#if SM4
        PixelShader = compile ps_4_0_level_9_1 PixelShaderFunction();
#else
        PixelShader = compile ps_3_0 PixelShaderFunction();
        VertexShader = compile vs_3_0 SpriteVertexShader();
#endif
    }
}
```

... compiles on both WindowsDX and DesktopGL, but it doesn't render on DesktopGL through `SpriteBatch.Begin(..., Effect, ...)`.

This can be worked around by removing the vertex shader...

```
float4 PixelShaderFunction(float4 position : SV_Position, float4 color : COLOR0, float2 tex : TEXCOORD0) : COLOR0
{
    return color * tex2D(s0, tex);
}

technique Blink
{
        pass Pass1
        {
#if SM4
                PixelShader = compile ps_4_0_level_9_1 PixelShaderFunction();
#else
                PixelShader = compile ps_3_0 PixelShaderFunction();             
#endif
        }
}
```

I believe there is something wrong with how DesktopGL sets the MatrixTransform. Maybe related to Z being inverted compared to DirectX?

Hi, 
in my project based on Monogame 3.4.0.459 I use TouchPanel class.

For example:

``` c#
protected override void Update(GameTime gameTime)   {

        graphics.ApplyChanges();

        TouchCollection touchCollection = TouchPanel.GetState();

        foreach (TouchLocation tl in touchCollection) {
                   //  ....(do something)... // 
        }
        base.Update(gameTime);
}
```

If I use Windows.DX package version everything works correctly, while using Windows.GL version TouchLocation  does not work because it does not capture touch action.

My OS for this test is Windows 10.

Currently the GamePad API does this internally:

```
if (index < 0 || index >= PlatformGetMaxNumberOfGamePads())
    throw new InvalidOperationException();
```

When you call GetState on an index outside the platform's maximum number of game pads, it throws an exception.  However, there's no public API for getting the value of `PlatformGetMaxNumberOfGamePads` (it is fully private), which means there's no way for a game to enumerate the list of supported gamepads without just cycling up to some number (e.g. 16) and catching exceptions.
